    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-02-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-02-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="455"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d455">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.24/2–2747</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandun by the Under Secretary of State for Economic
                        Affairs</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Clayton</hi>)<note n="1" xml:id="d455fn1"
                        >See footnote 1, <ref target="#pg_658">p. 658</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-02-27">February 27,
                            1947</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Further to my memorandum of February 26, 1947, paragraph 2, my recommendations
                    include pressing Soviet officials for affirmative responses to the requests in
                    our note of September 14, 1946 as follows:</p>
                <list>
                    <label>(1)</label>
                    <item>To set a definite date for initiation of lend-lease settlement discussions
                        in Washington. Any date prior to end of June would be considered
                        satisfactory.</item>
                    <label>(2)</label>
                    <item>To arrange immediately for the return to the United States or to make
                        application for purchase of U. S. merchant vessels in accordance with our
                        note of March 18, 1946.</item>
                    <label>(3)</label>
                    <item>To return immediately to the United States three Navy icebreakers in
                        accordance with our note of July 26, 1946.</item>
                </list>
                <p>Mr. Charles E. Bohlen and Mr. Elbridge Durbrow, Counselor of Embassy at Moscow,
                    are familiar with these matters.</p>
            </div>
